  "prompt": "What does the \"@\" symbol mean in Objective-C?",
  "response": "In Objective-C, the \"@\" symbol is used to denote various constructs that are specific to Objective-C and differentiate them from standard C code. Some key uses of the \"@\" symbol include:\n\n1. **Objective-C String Literals**: The \"@\" symbol is used to create NSString objects from string literals. For example:\n   ```objective-c\n   NSString *myString = @\"Hello, World!\";\n   ```\n   Here, `@\"Hello, World!\"` is an NSString literal.\n\n2. **Objective-C Keywords**: The \"@\" symbol is prefixed to certain keywords that are used for defining Objective-C-specific features, such as:\n   - `@interface` (used to declare a class interface)\n   - `@implementation` (used to define the implementation of the class)\n   - `@protocol` (used to declare a protocol)\n   - `@property` (used to declare a property)\n\n3. **Compiler Directives**: The \"@\" symbol is also used for certain compiler directives:\n   - `@synchronized` (used for synchronization, providing a mutex lock)\n   - `@try`, `@catch`, `@finally`, `@throw` (used for exception handling)\n\n4. **Objective-C Object Literals**: The \"@\" symbol is used for creating number, array, dictionary, and other object literals. For example:\n   ```objective-c\n   NSNumber *myNumber = @42;\n   NSArray *myArray = @[@\"Apple\", @\"Orange\", @\"Banana\"];\n   NSDictionary *myDictionary = @{@\"key1\": @\"value1\", @\"key2\": @\"value2\"};\n   ```\n\nThese uses of the \"@\" symbol help to create a clear distinction between Objective-C constructs and standard C code, making it easier to integrate object-oriented features and manage memory dynamically.",
